<sn><md>### Composition &amp; Formation{.text-center}

* Humus contains:

  * Polymerized aromatic molecules
  * Polysaccharides
  * Bound amino acids and proteins
  * Uronic acid polymers
  * Organo-phosphorus compounds
* Humus forms from **alteration of plant lignins, tannins, and phenolic substances**.
* **Microbial decomposition**:

  * Bacteria and fungi act first.
  * Actinomycetes dominate later stages.
* Favorable conditions:

  * Moisture (optimum)
  * Aeration (optimum)
  * pH 6–7.5
  * Temperature 30–45°C
</md></sn><sn><md>### Difference Between Organic and Inorganic (Clay) Soil Colloids

| Aspect                        | Organic Colloids (Humus)                                                                          | Inorganic Colloids (Clays)                                                   |
| ----------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Composition**               | Carbon, hydrogen, oxygen                                                                          | Aluminum, silicon, oxygen                                                    |
| **Structure &amp; Nature**        | Amorphous, complex; colloidal organic mixture; particle size similar to clay                      | Crystalline with well-defined structure                                      |
| **Stability**                 | Dynamic; formed and destroyed rapidly                                                             | Relatively static; change occurs mainly through long-term weathering         |
| **Structural Knowledge**      | Structure not well defined                                                                        | Crystal structure well known                                                 |
| **Source of Negative Charge** | Methoxyl, carboxylic (–COOH), enolic (–OH), phenolic –OH groups                                   | Isomorphous substitution and broken edges (permanent + pH-dependent charges) |
| **Charge Behavior**           | Strongly pH-dependent; low pH → H⁺ tightly bound, high pH → H⁺ ionizes and replaced by Ca²⁺, Mg²⁺ | Some pH-dependent, many permanent charges                                    |
</md></sn>